function minCostConnectPoints(points) {
    const n = points.length;
    const cost = new Array(n).fill(Infinity);
    const visited = new Array(n).fill(false);
    cost[0] = 0;

    let ans = 0;

    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        let min_cost = Infinity;
        let cur_point = -1;
        for (let j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if (!visited[j] && cost[j] < min_cost) {
                min_cost = cost[j];
                cur_point = j;
            }
        }

        visited[cur_point] = true;
        ans += min_cost;

        for (let j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if (!visited[j]) {
                const new_cost = Math.abs(points[cur_point][0] - points[j][0]) + Math.abs(points[cur_point][1] - points[j][1]);
                cost[j] = Math.min(cost[j], new_cost);
            }
        }
    }

    return ans;
}
```

    The solution uses Prim's algorithm for constructing a minimum spanning tree. Prim's algorithm maintains a tree of visited points and a set of unvisited points. Initially, the tree contains just one point (selected arbitrarily), and the set contains all other points. We repeat the following steps until all points are visited:

1. Find the point in the unvisited set with the minimum cost to connect it to any point in the visited set. Call this point the current point and add it to the visited set.
2. Update the costs of all unvisited points by calculating the Manhattan distance between the current point and each unvisited point. If this distance is smaller than the previously recorded cost for the unvisited point, replace the cost.

The total cost of the minimum spanning tree is the sum of connection costs for all points added to the visited set.

